<span id="freeTextContainer17678111738421961682">A plodding, somewhat meandering, low-key &quot;slice-of-life&quot; about the dual life of Yuichi, a rather generic figure whose only attribute is really a beauty that fascinates. It fails to reach the highs of other Mishima novels, and distinctly lacks the synthesis of death and beauty (except for a stilted philosophical monologue at the end of the book) that makes him such an interesting figure intellectually. This book would have been a lot better if it were ~200 pages, I feel. Ultimately just a boring </span>
  <span id="freeText17678111738421961682" style="display:none">A plodding, somewhat meandering, low-key "slice-of-life" about the dual life of Yuichi, a rather generic figure whose only attribute is really a beauty that fascinates. It fails to reach the highs of other Mishima novels, and distinctly lacks the synthesis of death and beauty (except for a stilted philosophical monologue at the end of the book) that makes him such an interesting figure intellectually. This book would have been a lot better if it were ~200 pages, I feel. Ultimately just a boring book, and while the beginning and end were pretty good, the ~300 page middle section doesn't really justify its length. A shame, as I really wanted to like this more!</span>
