    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_60119739" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/60119739" />
    <a title="Melissa" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2431320-melissa"><img alt="Melissa" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1245295069p2/2431320.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/60119739?book_show_action=true">Jun 17, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Melissa" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Melissa" href="/user/show/2431320-melissa">Melissa</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer60119739&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer60119739" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12694461544427053457">I just finished reading Forbidden Colors by Yukio Mishima, and I do not really know how I feel about it.<br/><br/>There were various points in the novel where I wanted to throw my book across the room in frustration. The main character, Yuichi, is nothing more than a spoiled Narcissus who can somehow be a perfect bastard and have nothing truly bad happen to him. He gets outed to his family by a vindictive old man after going out with said old man’s adopted “son” (aka kept boy) Minoru, and he just brings i</span>
  <span id="freeText12694461544427053457" style="display:none">I just finished reading Forbidden Colors by Yukio Mishima, and I do not really know how I feel about it.<br /><br />There were various points in the novel where I wanted to throw my book across the room in frustration. The main character, Yuichi, is nothing more than a spoiled Narcissus who can somehow be a perfect bastard and have nothing truly bad happen to him. He gets outed to his family by a vindictive old man after going out with said old man’s adopted “son” (aka kept boy) Minoru, and he just brings in a woman whose life he basically destroyed (and whose husband he was having an affair with). She basically makes excuses for him and gets him off the hook, and then takes him on a vacation all while thinking of how much she loves him. All the while Yuichi’s young wife and newborn baby are left behind. And about Minoru? Once he tired of him, once the boy became something he no longer desired to have, he dumped the boy who was caught up in his idealistic teenage hero-worship/love of Yuichi. Yuichi has no trouble dumping people like garbage, yet they love him still. It was unbelievable! Despite this, I did not hate him. Perhaps I had fallen under the same spell of this imaginary man that the characters in the book did? No… I do not think that was the case. As a woman, I could not really feel much but repugnance toward this mysoginistic bastard. But still, at various moments I felt he was going to redeem himself. Perhaps he would end up in an actual relationship with someone that was actually heartfelt, but whenever he got close he would end those relationships in cruel ways. Everyone loved him, yet he loved no one but himself. I could not like a main character like that. But the question stands: “Was I supposed to?”<br /><br />Considering Mishima’s biography, I cannot say. Was Mishima idealizing Yuichi? Was the fact that Yuichi got to live his life as he wished while destroying that of those around him just because he was beautiful portrayed as something “good”? I don’t know! 400 pages of philosophizing and bitterness and I am left without a good feel of the message. Maybe I don’t want to believe that all you need to get through life is an immaculate body. I refuse to accept that life is only for the beautiful and those they leave behind crushed under their feet after they’ve outlived their use. Is our destiny to be used and decimated by the Yuichis of the world? I don’t like to believe that Mishima was the kind of person to idealize the destruction of people’s lives while the one beautiful one prevails, but perhaps that was his message all along.<br /><br />I truly felt bad for the character of Yasuko, Yuichi’s wife. He marries her at Shunsuke’s inisitance and then ignores her for practically the entirety of the book. Only when it is convenient for him, in order to stoke his delusions and make himself feel better, he stays with her. She is largely tossed to the side until the end, in favor for Yuichi’s nightly excursions to the gay underworld of Tokyo (and he has many, many excursions… dude is a manslut). Here is this very young woman who is living a sad life all but abandoned by her husband. By the end she is so destroyed she decides to live without love, loving not even herself. Which left me wondering about their baby Keiko, who at one point Yuichi vows to groom into, well, something like himself. I weep for that child’s future!<br /><br />But as I said, I did not hate Yuichi. I understood where his hatred and attitude came from. Anyone born into a society where they are not accepted for who they are and forced to act to fit with the “norms” will become resentful of that. His (and Shunsuke’s, the old novelist who gets the ball rolling, so to speak) hatred toward women, for however different and twisted their reasoning, are somehow understandable. And Yuichi will of course, as any person probably would, was intoxicated by his own beauty that everyone constantly praised him for. His narcissism wasn’t solely the result of him noticing he was beautiful and then all of a sudden deciding his beauty made it okay for him to destroy the lives of others. Shunsuke can shoulder the blame for awakening and feeding the dragon that Yuichi became. Does that make it acceptable? No, not really. It does, though, create the feeling that while he’s a shamless asshole, he’s a shameless asshole for a reason, however underlying that reason may be. It just sucks that his behaviors were rewarded with people falling in love with him left and right, countless excursions and gifts and 10,100,000 yen. If I were him I’d feel empty and lifeless, but while he skirts around these feelings that he wants to/is changing, ultimately he can live with himself as he came to be.<br /><br />I don’t really know. Forbidden Colors was long, infinitely frustrating, convoluted, and difficult to understand at times, but alongside that it was stunning, disturbing, and fascinating. I didn’t feel happy when I finished reading. I felt drained and bewildered, but not regretful.<br /><br />I had another Mishima book lined up as my next read, but at nearly 400 pages I’m not sure I want to read it. Forbidden Colors took me halfway on a journey through a desert, and now that I’ve reached an oasis I am not sure I want to finish that journey any time soon…<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="12694461544427053457" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


