    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1202114858" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1202114858" />
    <a title="Patrick" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8255719-patrick"><img alt="Patrick" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1332087637p2/8255719.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1202114858?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Patrick" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Patrick" href="/user/show/8255719-patrick">Patrick</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141189567" href="/book/show/6054171-forbidden-colours">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1202114858" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5946527181535283099">I knew very little about the author before reading this, only those few things that are the common facts to anyone familiar with his name: that for a long time he was perhaps the most internationally renowned Japanese novelist, that he was nominated three times for the Nobel prize, and that he died one of the most unusual deaths of any writer in the twentieth century. Reading around him a little, I soon found that in recent biographical essays those points tend to overshadow the rest of his life</span>
  <span id="freeText5946527181535283099" style="display:none">I knew very little about the author before reading this, only those few things that are the common facts to anyone familiar with his name: that for a long time he was perhaps the most internationally renowned Japanese novelist, that he was nominated three times for the Nobel prize, and that he died one of the most unusual deaths of any writer in the twentieth century. Reading around him a little, I soon found that in recent biographical essays those points tend to overshadow the rest of his life to a surprising degree. It’s a rather depressing thought; he was, after all, enormously prolific, and for his end to be regarded as the most important fact of his life seems to me rather a backwards way of looking at things. <br /><br />But I’m getting distracted — in writing this, perhaps I too have fallen prey to that same morbid, romantic fascination with an act which seems to have come directly from an alien culture. On a personal level, I find it difficult to relate to the author’s fierce nationalism; but then we have nothing in Britain to compare with the rich and ancient warrior traditions to which he subscribed. His notions of gender and sexuality are strange and complex, quite alien to my own, but I think they need to be read in the context of a post-war society struggling with modernity, occupation, and the catastrophic aftermath of war. <br /><br />Not that any of these aspects are initially prominent. What we have, to begin with, is something fairly familiar: in form, the book has many of the aspects of a conventional late-nineteenth century novel. It is story of relatively affluent society, of the social peccadilloes of middle class families in a modern society. The characters are complex, detailed creations, and there’s a narrative focus on psychological interiors in the vein of Joseph Conrad or Henry James. Much writing is spent on explaining to the reader the innermost thoughts and desires of the small circle of people in which the story moves.<br /><br />In the opening pages we encounter Shinsuké, a famous novelist in his twilight years. While holidaying alone, he meets a young couple, Yasuko and her boyfriend Yuichi. Shinsuké is fascinated by the incomparable beauty of this young man, and recognises in him certain traits familiar to himself: he’s gay, but this boy also finds something essentially repulsive in women. The older man is convinced that they are unlovable, and he preys on Yuichi’s distance from Yasuko, and the shame he feels in being unable to approach her. So he does what any rabid misogynist might do: he makes Yuichi a thoroughly indecent proposal. He will pay Yuichi ¥500,000 if he marries Yasuko while also living a double-life of gay affairs, as a kind of puppet for the elderly author: his final creation to cap off a career mostly spent belittling women in prose. Yasuko will be hurt - a delightful thought to him - and Shinsuké will have the opportunity of living vicariously a life he never previously had the chance to experience.<br /><br />Summarised like this, the plot is fairly unusual, to put it kindly. And yet it builds elegantly into a compelling narrative; there’s plenty of action, with the thing ultimately revolving around a series of interlocking bizarre love triangles. Shinsuké himself is a strange creation — we clearly aren’t supposed to like him, yet his philosophical monologues possess a peculiar magnetism. By modern standards there’s a great deal that is repulsive in the author’s presentation of promiscuous gay culture, yet there is also a great deal of care and depth languished over the loving feelings of characters both gay and straight. It is a strange book, possessed of cynicism without being in itself cynical. There is no true romantic love to be found here. Instead it carries with it the suggestion that the only lasting, meaningful relationships are those which stand up to the kind of terrible and messy human strain that no conception of polite and courtly love could ever encompass.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5946527181535283099" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


