<div id="review_3139661762" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3139661762" />
    <a title="Zach" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32734318-zach"><img alt="Zach" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1617954547p2/32734318.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3139661762?book_show_action=true">Jan 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Zach" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Zach" href="/user/show/32734318-zach">Zach</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3139661762" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2369358906192216307">mishima describes the gay mores before destroying and reassembling it nearly two decades before its popular conception in the west. not quite the homofascist misogyny tornado a lot seem to read it as (i&apos;m firmly convinced the text&apos;s hatred of women exists only in the characters and not in the actual theme) but nevertheless a damning and often evil exercise in beauty. i love yuichi as much as these women and men do; it is painful to experience. so philosophically contrived and dense it cannot be </span>
  <span id="freeText2369358906192216307" style="display:none">mishima describes the gay mores before destroying and reassembling it nearly two decades before its popular conception in the west. not quite the homofascist misogyny tornado a lot seem to read it as (i'm firmly convinced the text's hatred of women exists only in the characters and not in the actual theme) but nevertheless a damning and often evil exercise in beauty. i love yuichi as much as these women and men do; it is painful to experience. so philosophically contrived and dense it cannot be singularly described with one theme. if i were to try, i'd say it's that surrendering to the vulnerability of love and the appeal of aesthetic is fatal. making love tangible is futile and horrible, especially for gay men trapped in a world in which their desires are shackled to snack bars and cruising grounds, aloha shirts, rejections upon rejections. whether you are seeing or are being seen, you are doomed by beauty.<br /><br />can't quite say what the conclusion is, except that it's brutal. overall very imperfect. <br /><br />"someone once said that homosexuals have on their faces a certain loneliness that will not come off."</span>
  <a data-text-id="2369358906192216307" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review3139661762">
  <td colspan="2">
    <div class="updateActionLinks">
