<div id="review_3556554201" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3556554201" />
    <a title="Nermine Tadross" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/22264069-nermine-tadross"><img alt="Nermine Tadross" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1489687348p2/22264069.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3556554201?book_show_action=true">Sep 19, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Nermine Tadross" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Nermine Tadross" href="/user/show/22264069-nermine-tadross">Nermine Tadross</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3556554201" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16574274960883232694">I&apos;ve just finished my fifth novel by Japanese Avant-Garde author Yukio Mishima. Forbidden Colors (1951-1953) is an early work which is usually categorized as LGBT literature but it can be read and enjoyed in more than one level.<br/>Set against the backdrop of the the gay underworld of postwar Japan, the story is about revenge; an old author uses a beautiful and &quot;innocent&quot; young homosexual student to revenge his failed past relationships with women. Yuichi Minami (YM indicates some autobiographical e</span>
  <span id="freeText16574274960883232694" style="display:none">I've just finished my fifth novel by Japanese Avant-Garde author Yukio Mishima. Forbidden Colors (1951-1953) is an early work which is usually categorized as LGBT literature but it can be read and enjoyed in more than one level.<br />Set against the backdrop of the the gay underworld of postwar Japan, the story is about revenge; an old author uses a beautiful and "innocent" young homosexual student to revenge his failed past relationships with women. Yuichi Minami (YM indicates some autobiographical elements!) becomes a suitable weapon to avenge the aged author's wounded ego.<br />Mishima goes to very dark places in the human psyche, including his own, and keeps probing and analyzing till he's satisfied and then puts his findings as fully realized characters. Every character is psychologically depicted in such an impressive way! The self-centered, emotionally detached yet gullible protagonist, the puppet master who employs him as a weapon of revenge, the loving but passive wife who's trying to forgive,the shocked mother whose main concern is that her son is not a homosexual, the beautiful middle aged wife who finds it hard not to fall in love with her husband's lover, the haughty lover who needs to free himself from a destructive relationship and many others are there to form a unique minutely detailed painting.<br />Forbidden Colors is not just about the story of revenge or finding sexual identity but it's more about the philosophical debate on art, the artist and the artistic creation. Does the work of art belong to itself or its creator? The symbolic level here is very interesting to look at too.It is also more of a contemplation of the transient nature of beauty. Indeed one sentence in the book reveals Mishima's aesthetic and personal believe: "What is the death of the body, after all, compared with the unbearable death of youth?" This theme was more deeply and maturely discussed in Mishima's later philosophical masterpiece The Temple of the Golden Pavilion (1956) but here one can clearly see the beginning of a great talent about to erupt.<br />Mishima's beautiful prose is almost baroque at some passages and full of Greek mythological references. The first time we see Yuichi coming out from a swim is a retelling of the birth of Venus myth in which the goddess is born from the sea foam but we soon find out that he's more of a Narcissus living in a house of mirrors. References to other Greek mythological figures like Hippolytus, Adonis and others populate the book and give its examination of beauty a more profound classical meaning.<br />But, for me, the most important scene is that when Yuichi watches the birth of his child and at this moment all the mirrors he was imprisoned inside are no more and he's able to see others as well not just his reflection: "Narcissus had forgotten his own face. His eyes had another object than the mirror."<br />If you enjoyed James Baldwin's Giovanni's Room, Thomas Mann's Death in Venice (Mishima was a huge Mann's fan) and Pierre Choderlos de Laclos'cruel mind games in Dangerous Liaison then you'd also enjoy Forbidden Colors.<br />Naturally in a book that its subject matter involves revenge from Women a lot of misogyny is expected especially with the repression of homosexuality and arranged marriage at the time in Japan. So if this kind of discourse bothers you don't read this one and start with Mishima's debut novel Confessions of a Mask instead.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16574274960883232694" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

